{
  "format": "tiptap/v1",
  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Pooling Problem"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A transformer encoder like BERT outputs one vector per input token. For a sentence with 5 tokens, that means 5 vectors each of dimension 768. But downstream tasks — semantic search, clustering, classification — need a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "single fixed-size vector"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " representing the whole sentence. Pooling is the operation that collapses those token vectors into one."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The choice of pooling strategy has a large effect on downstream quality. The wrong strategy can cut benchmark performance nearly in half."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Four pooling strategies: [CLS] token, mean pooling (SBERT default), max pooling, and weighted mean — with STS benchmark Spearman ρ comparison bars"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Strategy 1: [CLS] Token"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "BERT prepends a special "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "[CLS]"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " token and its final hidden state is designed (via Next Sentence Prediction pre-training) to summarize the whole sequence. Taking this vector directly is the simplest possible pooling strategy."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from transformers import AutoTokenizer, AutoModel\nimport torch\n\ntokenizer = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained(\"bert-base-uncased\")\nmodel = AutoModel.from_pretrained(\"bert-base-uncased\")\n\nsentence = \"The cat sat on the mat\"\ninputs = tokenizer(sentence, return_tensors=\"pt\")\n\nwith torch.no_grad():\n    outputs = model(**inputs)\n\n# [CLS] is always position 0\ncls_embedding = outputs.last_hidden_state[:, 0, :]  # shape: (1, 768)\nprint(cls_embedding.shape)  # torch.Size([1, 768])"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The problem: BERT's NSP objective was designed for sentence-pair classification, not for producing geometrically meaningful sentence vectors. Without fine-tuning for semantic similarity, "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "[CLS]"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " vectors produce very poor cosine similarities — the STS-B Spearman ρ is around 0.30, barely above chance."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Strategy 2: Mean Pooling"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Average the token embeddings for all real (non-padding) tokens, typically excluding "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "[CLS]"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " and "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "[SEP]"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". With attention mask "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "italic"
              }
            ],
            "text": "m"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " indicating which positions are real tokens:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\mathbf{s} = \\frac{\\sum_{i=1}^{T} m_i \\, \\mathbf{h}_i}{\\sum_{i=1}^{T} m_i}"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "This is the "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "default in sentence-transformers"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " and consistently outperforms other strategies without fine-tuning. The attention mask division handles variable-length sequences and padding correctly."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "def mean_pool(token_embeddings, attention_mask):\n    \"\"\"Mask-aware mean pooling over real tokens.\"\"\"\n    # Expand mask to match embedding dimension\n    mask_expanded = attention_mask.unsqueeze(-1).float()  # (B, T, 1)\n    # Zero out padding token embeddings\n    summed = (token_embeddings * mask_expanded).sum(dim=1)  # (B, 768)\n    # Divide by actual token count per sample\n    count = mask_expanded.sum(dim=1).clamp(min=1e-9)       # (B, 1)\n    return summed / count\n\n\nsentences = [\"The cat sat\", \"A dog ran quickly through the park\"]\ninputs = tokenizer(sentences, return_tensors=\"pt\", padding=True, truncation=True)\n\nwith torch.no_grad():\n    outputs = model(**inputs)\n\nembeddings = mean_pool(outputs.last_hidden_state, inputs[\"attention_mask\"])\nprint(embeddings.shape)  # (2, 768)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Strategy 3: Max Pooling"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Take the element-wise maximum across all token positions for each embedding dimension:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "s_k = \\max_{i=1}^{T} h_{i,k} \\quad \\text{for each dimension } k"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Max pooling captures the strongest feature activation in each dimension. Intuitively, if any token strongly signals a feature (e.g. dimension 42 encodes \"financial context\"), the max preserves that signal even if only one token triggers it. This makes it useful for classification tasks where the presence of a feature matters more than its average intensity."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "def max_pool(token_embeddings, attention_mask):\n    \"\"\"Element-wise max over real (non-padded) token positions.\"\"\"\n    # Replace padding positions with a very large negative number\n    # so they don't win the max\n    mask_expanded = attention_mask.unsqueeze(-1).float()\n    token_embeddings[mask_expanded == 0] = -1e9\n    return token_embeddings.max(dim=1).values  # (B, 768)\n\nembeddings = max_pool(outputs.last_hidden_state.clone(), inputs[\"attention_mask\"])\nprint(embeddings.shape)  # (2, 768)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Strategy 4: Weighted / Attention Pooling"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Learn a scalar attention weight "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "italic"
              }
            ],
            "text": "α"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " for each token position and form a weighted average:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\mathbf{s} = \\sum_{i=1}^{T} \\alpha_i \\, \\mathbf{h}_i, \\quad \\alpha_i = \\frac{\\exp(\\mathbf{w}^\\top \\mathbf{h}_i)}{\\sum_j \\exp(\\mathbf{w}^\\top \\mathbf{h}_j)}"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The attention vector "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "w"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " is a learned parameter. The model can learn to up-weight content words and down-weight function words or punctuation. Some SBERT variants (e.g. models with a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "WeightedLayerPooling"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " module) extend this across transformer layers rather than across positions."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import torch.nn as nn\n\nclass AttentionPooling(nn.Module):\n    def __init__(self, hidden_size: int):\n        super().__init__()\n        self.attention = nn.Linear(hidden_size, 1)\n\n    def forward(self, token_embeddings, attention_mask):\n        # Score each token\n        scores = self.attention(token_embeddings).squeeze(-1)  # (B, T)\n        # Mask padding before softmax\n        scores = scores.masked_fill(attention_mask == 0, -1e9)\n        weights = scores.softmax(dim=-1).unsqueeze(-1)         # (B, T, 1)\n        return (token_embeddings * weights).sum(dim=1)          # (B, 768)\n\npooler = AttentionPooling(hidden_size=768)\nembeddings = pooler(outputs.last_hidden_state, inputs[\"attention_mask\"])\nprint(embeddings.shape)  # (2, 768)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Strategy Comparison"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "table",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "tableRow",
